          "body": "The chapter opens with the familiar Judges framework (6:1) but slows to describe the oppression with unusual specificity. The Midianites do not occupy the land permanently; they come seasonally, at harvest, with the precision of a scythe (6:3-4). The locust-simile (6:5) is not rhetorical decoration — it describes an economic strategy: allow Israel to plant, then arrive to consume. The result is starvation. Israel retreats to mountain dens (6:2); the valleys — the productive heart of Canaan — belong to the enemy. The author of Judges is writing covenant theology in the key of agricultural suffering. The land that was supposed to flow with milk and honey now flows to Gaza in the hands of strangers (6:4). Deuteronomy 28:33 had warned exactly this: 'A people whom you do not know shall eat up the produce of your ground.' Seven years of that is not accidental; it is the covenant's warning made literal. The cry of 6:6-7 is not merely emotional distress — it is the covenant's built-in mechanism: oppression → cry → divine attention. The question is always whether the cry comes from repentance or merely from pain."
